         <abstract>
            <p>A B&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;-sequence is a sequence a&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt; &lt; a&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; &lt; ⋯ &lt; a&lt;sub&gt;r&lt;/sub&gt; of positive integers such that the sums a&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt; + a&lt;sub&gt;j&lt;/sub&gt;, 1 ≤ i ≤ j ≤ r, are different. When q is a power of a prime and θ is a primitive element in GF (q&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;) then there are B&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;-sequences A(q, θ) of size q with a&lt;sub&gt;q&lt;/sub&gt; &lt; q&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;, which were discovered by R. C. Bose and S. Chowla. In Theorem 2.1 I will give a faster alternative to the definition. In Theorem 2.2 I will prove that multiplying a sequence A (q, θ) by integers relatively prime to the modulus is equivalent to varying θ. Theorem 3.1 is my main result. It contains a fast method to find primitive quadratic polynomials over GF(p) when p is an odd prime. For fields of characteristic 2 there is a similar, but different, criterion, which I will consider in "Primitive quadratics reflected in B&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;-sequences", to appear in Portugaliae Mathematica (1999).</p>
          </abstract>
